1
00:00:01,820 --> 00:00:28,214
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambudasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambudasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambudasa

2
00:00:28,195 --> 00:00:33,023
Homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:37,289 --> 00:00:38,451
Right, so...

4
00:00:45,703 --> 00:00:51,131
This talk came about because a friend of mine, who's a musician...

5
00:00:51,549 --> 00:00:55,655
wanted to write music around the theme of Angulimala, as some of you may know.

6
00:00:55,676 --> 00:01:01,505
And the story of Angulimala is a murdering thief.

7
00:01:02,746 --> 00:01:09,456
But he meets the Buddha and undertakes the training and before he dies becomes fully enlightened.

8
00:01:09,475 --> 00:01:10,317
So there's hope for us all.

9
00:01:13,022 --> 00:01:20,072
And he wanted me to write, as it were, something which he could attach his music to.

10
00:01:20,996 --> 00:01:33,829
and having done that I wanted to add something to it to explain the psychology as to how somebody so steeped in evil might arrive at the enlightenment even within this very lifetime.

11
00:01:35,251 --> 00:01:47,763
So the first part I'll ask you to do some imaginative work and then we'll do some explanation

12
00:01:48,469 --> 00:02:02,543
And then at the end you can try and have a go at practicing forgiving all those people whom you've murdered and forgiving yourself, rather, and forgiving all those people who've done you harm.

13
00:02:03,305 --> 00:02:03,626
Okay.

14
00:02:04,929 --> 00:02:05,870
So...

15
00:02:10,846 --> 00:02:12,828
Just try this one for size, shall we say.

16
00:02:13,127 --> 00:02:20,435
You can close your eyes and just, what I want you to try and do, and just catch the process of your psychology.

17
00:02:23,798 --> 00:02:35,269
Just imagine now, if you can think of an actual occasion in your life, that might be even better, but just think of an occasion now where somebody says something which hurts you.

18
00:02:35,590 --> 00:02:39,233
It might be just a flippant thing, like you're an idiot or something.

19
00:02:41,254 --> 00:02:44,680
So if you can imagine that, and just let the insult come.

20
00:02:45,501 --> 00:02:47,943
Now, just catch your reaction.

21
00:03:00,862 --> 00:03:02,504
So I wonder what the reaction might have been.

22
00:03:02,544 --> 00:03:04,348
Irritation?

23
00:03:04,888 --> 00:03:05,248
Anger?

24
00:03:05,269 --> 00:03:06,030
Indignation?

25
00:03:09,453 --> 00:03:13,182
And what might it lead you to once you've left that person?

26
00:03:14,225 --> 00:03:15,469
What might it lead you to?

27
00:03:15,490 --> 00:03:19,219
A slander?

28
00:03:20,082 --> 00:03:20,965
A knife in the back?

29
00:03:28,893 --> 00:03:31,355
So now just try something else on a similar line.

30
00:03:32,257 --> 00:03:38,484
Instead of somebody saying something awful to you, they actually do something to you.

31
00:03:39,185 --> 00:03:48,816
Perhaps they push you, or they stick their finger into you, or at worst they bop you on the nose.

32
00:03:51,138 --> 00:03:51,919
Can you imagine that?

33
00:03:52,759 --> 00:03:54,461
Can you see what your reaction might be?

34
00:04:09,932 --> 00:04:15,218
I would suggest it's much the same unless they're much bigger than you then you'd probably get a bit fearful.

35
00:04:19,202 --> 00:04:32,838
So the question we have to ask ourselves is did that person cause us suffering?

36
00:04:32,858 --> 00:04:37,863
Do you think they were the direct cause of your suffering?

37
00:04:44,543 --> 00:04:49,031
So now turn that one around now and just take somebody whom you're going to insult.

38
00:04:50,475 --> 00:04:50,735
Okay?

39
00:04:51,656 --> 00:04:55,124
It might be the same person of course.

40
00:04:55,163 --> 00:05:02,197
So as you just make that scene in your mind, you see, offer them your insult and just see how you feel about that.

41
00:05:14,529 --> 00:05:17,473
I would suggest that maybe you feel a little satisfied by it.

42
00:05:17,675 --> 00:05:18,675
Sort of a job well done.

43
00:05:19,276 --> 00:05:20,137
Sort of pleased.

44
00:05:26,728 --> 00:05:31,254
Supposing they pushed in front of you in a queue or something.

45
00:05:31,795 --> 00:05:34,658
You got rather angry about it and you sort of pushed them out.

46
00:05:36,281 --> 00:05:38,043
You used a bit of physical force there.

47
00:05:39,586 --> 00:05:40,807
Can you imagine yourself doing that?

48
00:05:52,177 --> 00:05:56,483
So I would suggest it's much the same as above, only a little more stronger.

49
00:06:07,016 --> 00:06:18,451
Now take that person and let them come back to you and say that they're really upset and you've seen that you've been the cause of their being upset.

50
00:06:20,454 --> 00:06:21,696
Now how do you feel about that?

51
00:06:34,822 --> 00:06:37,786
a little remorseful, a bit guilty, shame.

52
00:06:40,250 --> 00:06:46,079
Let's take an occasion which is much worse.

53
00:06:46,119 --> 00:06:53,790
Supposing you've unfortunately had one or two drinks and you knock somebody over on the road.

54
00:06:56,495 --> 00:06:59,959
Now what's your first reaction there?

55
00:07:01,101 --> 00:07:02,584
Just play it through your mind.

56
00:07:12,959 --> 00:07:29,937
shock, fear dread of consequences when other people find out shame when you realize what you've done to the person remorse

57
00:07:40,110 --> 00:07:57,651
That's the end of our little escapade of trying to imagine things, just to get you in touch, as it were, with all those emotions, all those states of mind that revolve around those actions where we're hurting somebody or somebody's hurting us.

58
00:07:59,312 --> 00:08:09,644
So now, if we just take the process of that psychology, what we have, of course, is the Wheel of Dependent Origination.

59
00:08:10,874 --> 00:08:20,242
And what the Buddha is teaching us there is that whatever, just taking the first instance, whatever somebody does to us,

60
00:08:22,382 --> 00:08:27,930
has to stop at the point of reception, at the point where we perceive something.

61
00:08:28,870 --> 00:08:35,080
So if somebody, you know, called me, you know, you fathead, that's not very nice, is it?

62
00:08:35,779 --> 00:08:42,509
They call me fathead, you see, so what actually happens is that I've just heard these words, fathead.

63
00:08:43,791 --> 00:08:52,322
If somebody, then having heard those words, I take them into myself.

64
00:08:52,639 --> 00:08:58,910
I take them into myself and I define them as unpleasant.

65
00:09:00,653 --> 00:09:01,254
They are, aren't they?

66
00:09:01,895 --> 00:09:02,998
So they're unpleasant.

67
00:09:03,018 --> 00:09:08,466
So this person hasn't actually made me think they're unpleasant.

68
00:09:09,708 --> 00:09:12,653
I'm just defining them as unpleasant within myself.

69
00:09:14,216 --> 00:09:16,520
If I didn't speak English I'd probably smile.

70
00:09:17,783 --> 00:09:45,782
so there's something I've done there whereby I've defined this as unpleasant now I've taught myself that when something unpleasant arises I have to get rid of it I want to push it away so that's my reaction to something unpleasant and again it's done by me within me because of my past conditioning now

71
00:09:46,960 --> 00:09:58,394
So we can see if we look at our psychology very carefully, the person who's called us fathead hasn't actually caused me to suffer.

72
00:09:58,974 --> 00:10:00,576
It's the way I've responded to it.

73
00:10:02,979 --> 00:10:11,909
If the person who's just called me fathead is reckoned by everybody just to be a bit loopy, then I wouldn't have that reaction.

74
00:10:11,990 --> 00:10:14,773
I'd probably just say, oh, well, they're a bit daft or something.

75
00:10:16,221 --> 00:10:37,268
so everything all the hurt that I get when somebody insults me or somebody says something cruel to me is my own inner reaction these I can't blame them for making me suffer

76
00:10:40,284 --> 00:10:48,258
If somebody now pulls my nose, or tugs my ears, or gives me a shove, where does that stop?

77
00:10:48,839 --> 00:10:50,581
It stops at the physical body, doesn't it?

78
00:10:50,822 --> 00:10:52,585
It stops at a sensation on the body.

79
00:10:56,130 --> 00:11:06,748
But then, inwardly, I see what the person's done, I feel what the person's done to me, and again, I define it as unpleasant.

80
00:11:06,897 --> 00:11:10,562
Again, I respond to it with irritation, with anger, with hurt.

81
00:11:11,724 --> 00:11:16,010
But that's all happening in me as a response to what this person has done.

82
00:11:21,298 --> 00:11:25,424
I can't say that this person has made me suffer.

83
00:11:28,448 --> 00:11:33,596
They've given me, shall we say, severe sensations on the nose.

84
00:11:34,032 --> 00:11:40,058
which I've defined as pain, but pain isn't suffering.

85
00:11:40,879 --> 00:11:44,565
Pain as such is just sensation, no matter how severe it is.

86
00:11:45,765 --> 00:11:53,335
What makes us suffer, what makes it hard to stay with, is our reaction to it, our inability to be patient with it.

87
00:11:55,357 --> 00:12:00,663
So it's the internal reaction we have to these things which is actually causing us to suffer.

88
00:12:06,128 --> 00:12:14,721
So those are your links on this wheel of bent origination which remember is the Buddha's paradigm as to how we cause suffering for ourselves.

89
00:12:16,344 --> 00:12:17,846
How we cause suffering for ourselves.

90
00:12:19,369 --> 00:12:29,083
So now you can widen that out and you begin to recognize that nobody in the world can cause you psychological pain.

91
00:12:32,629 --> 00:12:32,710
See?

92
00:12:34,090 --> 00:12:39,095
which is hard to accept because until now we've been very happy blaming everybody else.

93
00:12:41,716 --> 00:12:48,043
Parents, society, Tony Blair, all these people have made me suffer, you see.

94
00:12:48,344 --> 00:12:54,028
But now when I look into my psychology, I can't say that anymore.

95
00:12:57,652 --> 00:13:03,658
If we now turn it the other way, I now say to somebody, you fathead,

96
00:13:04,820 --> 00:13:09,566
Now, the same process is happening within them.

97
00:13:09,586 --> 00:13:19,677
I can't say that I've caused them to suffer, but I have to recognize what's happening in me.

98
00:13:21,679 --> 00:13:29,950
What's happening in me is that I am developing a conditioning of hate, a conditioning of cruelty.

99
00:13:33,894 --> 00:13:52,798
Now I might get immediate satisfaction by watching somebody cringe when I call them you fathead, but inside me I have this turbulence, this desire to be cruel, this desire to get my own back, the hatred within me.

100
00:13:55,275 --> 00:14:01,062
And of course the effect of that is that, not surprisingly, people start staying away.

101
00:14:01,943 --> 00:14:02,784
They don't hang about.

102
00:14:03,405 --> 00:14:04,326
They don't want to talk to me.

103
00:14:07,010 --> 00:14:14,240
So my cruelty, my hatred, goes into the world and the world moves away from me.

104
00:14:14,259 --> 00:14:19,966
And it causes me to be lonely, etc., etc., and if I don't see that, I then blame others.

105
00:14:20,452 --> 00:14:27,722
for not being friendly, for not being open-hearted to me, and I begin to hate them the more.

106
00:14:30,167 --> 00:14:42,023
I'm in a sort of whirlwind, taking me downwards into a sort of perpetual state of hatred and grumbling and whinging, which can keep you awake.

107
00:14:44,601 --> 00:14:50,429
Worse still, if I actually hit somebody or push somebody, then that's a more violent act.

108
00:14:51,932 --> 00:14:54,815
And therefore the inner violence is even worse.

109
00:14:57,879 --> 00:15:06,070
So here we have a situation where I think I'm hurting somebody, but in fact I'm only hurting myself.

110
00:15:11,315 --> 00:15:16,681
So you might ask, well, what stops you from hurting somebody anyway, you see?

111
00:15:19,063 --> 00:15:38,706
Well, when we've contacted the hurt that I feel when somebody insults me or somebody harms me, then even though I recognize that I'm the cause of it, it's out of compassion for the other that you don't.

112
00:15:39,427 --> 00:15:44,255
that you are not the catalyst whereby they cause themselves to suffer.

113
00:15:45,557 --> 00:16:02,904
So you begin to take responsibility not to enter into situations, not to confront people in such a way that you know you're just pressing their buttons.

114
00:16:13,144 --> 00:16:21,977
So, the whole psychology around doing harm is always centred on us.

115
00:16:24,100 --> 00:16:36,519
We ourselves create an inner turbulence when we do harm, and when somebody does harm to us, it's we that create within us our own suffering.

116
00:16:36,538 --> 00:16:41,986
Now, although that may seem at first

117
00:16:43,368 --> 00:16:51,620
to land us in a load of suffering is the very fact that we create our own suffering that will allow us to escape it in the end.

118
00:16:53,023 --> 00:16:55,186
That's the purpose of meditation.

119
00:16:55,206 --> 00:16:56,467
That's the purpose of vipassana.

120
00:16:57,408 --> 00:17:01,274
So you can see these mechanisms that are causing us to suffer.

121
00:17:02,605 --> 00:17:12,515
And then you realize that you must stop behaving like that, which means that in your daily life you have to maintain that sense of sharp mindfulness, knowing your own habits.

122
00:17:13,796 --> 00:17:17,319
Even if you respond in an old way, you don't indulge it.

123
00:17:18,099 --> 00:17:23,566
Even though somebody says to you, you fathead, you see, it stays right there at the point of hurt.

124
00:17:24,125 --> 00:17:30,772
You're prepared to let the hurt hurt because you know that is your own personal response to such a thing.

125
00:17:31,546 --> 00:17:37,595
But you don't allow yourself to begin to fantasize to get your own back.

126
00:17:37,615 --> 00:17:43,923
So if somebody insults you once, as you know, by the end of the day, they've insulted you a thousand times.

127
00:17:45,165 --> 00:17:47,429
And the punishment for their insult has got worse.

128
00:17:48,170 --> 00:17:50,333
At first, you just shouted at them in your mind.

129
00:17:50,953 --> 00:17:53,557
But by the time you go to bed, you're hanging them.

130
00:17:54,459 --> 00:17:56,321
You're chucking them out of the window.

131
00:17:56,960 --> 00:18:09,000
So remember, it's through the process of thinking and fantasizing that we are developing these states of mind.

132
00:18:09,682 --> 00:18:15,211
This is how we develop our states of mind, through fantasy, through this process of thinking.

133
00:18:16,313 --> 00:18:22,123
And it's not a great distance between thinking about doing something and actually doing it.

134
00:18:23,587 --> 00:18:33,396
So what the vipassana or the insight meditation is teaching us to do is to stay right there with the hurt, to let the hurt die away.

135
00:18:34,637 --> 00:18:52,194
Now, when the hurt dies away, first of all, we're stopping it developing, but more important, we're actually undercutting that old conditioning of being hurt when somebody calls us a name or does something which insults us.

136
00:18:53,423 --> 00:19:04,598
but actually going underneath it so that there will come a time when somebody might say something which in the past you would have felt to be hurtful but actually it just stops at the sense door.

137
00:19:04,858 --> 00:19:05,941
You just hear the word.

138
00:19:06,342 --> 00:19:07,522
There isn't that reaction.

139
00:19:09,065 --> 00:19:20,561
So you can see that taking full responsibility for our inner suffering using the vipassana to allow things to burn out and to heal

140
00:19:21,182 --> 00:19:46,228
is actually the process of psychotherapy healing the heart purifying the heart that would be impossible to do if you think the other person is making you suffer in which case you'd have to change everybody in the world because a lot of people going around go around calling other people fatheads so even though

141
00:19:47,321 --> 00:19:51,866
It's difficult sometimes for us to recognize that nobody can hurt us.

142
00:19:52,528 --> 00:19:54,911
Actually, that's our salvation.

143
00:19:55,030 --> 00:19:55,832
That's the healing.

144
00:19:56,173 --> 00:19:57,934
That's the liberation from suffering.

145
00:19:58,615 --> 00:19:59,977
Once we've actually realized that.

146
00:20:09,588 --> 00:20:13,313
With that, there's the other side where we hurt people.

147
00:20:14,221 --> 00:20:34,119
So it's recognizing that even though we can't cause somebody to suffer, by actually wanting to hurt people, we're creating a turbulence within our mind, which is suffering, and we're creating a habit, we're creating a habit, which eventually begins to push people away from us.

148
00:20:36,866 --> 00:21:04,613
so once we recognize that there's a sort of the serpent bites back the serpent is biting its own tail then you realize that that sort of behavior has to stop so again the purpose of the vipassana is to sit with it in silence to allow it to burn away but then we have to maintain that sense of sharp mindfulness in daily life

149
00:21:04,593 --> 00:21:06,914
so that we don't fall into those old habits.

150
00:21:08,737 --> 00:21:18,665
And what we discover is that very slowly, over a period of time, you know, 20 odd years, those habits of trying to do harm to everybody just fade away.

151
00:21:18,705 --> 00:21:22,269
And the opposite, of course, takes its place.

152
00:21:22,608 --> 00:21:23,849
Nature abhors a vacuum.

153
00:21:24,211 --> 00:21:26,172
We're talking here about transformation.

154
00:21:26,633 --> 00:21:28,894
So where there was cruelty, now there's compassion.

155
00:21:29,655 --> 00:21:31,196
Where there's hate, now there's love.

156
00:21:31,217 --> 00:21:31,938
There's openness.

157
00:21:32,397 --> 00:21:33,459
There's open-heartedness.

158
00:21:33,638 --> 00:21:34,599
Warm-heartedness.

159
00:21:38,224 --> 00:21:46,175
Just as a little aside, just talking about these things that we suffer.

160
00:21:47,238 --> 00:21:56,171
So for instance, we have within us a mechanism that decides whether something is good or bad, skillful or unskillful.

161
00:21:56,652 --> 00:21:57,813
We call it our conscience.

162
00:21:59,816 --> 00:22:02,460
Now, just because...

163
00:22:03,148 --> 00:22:32,109
our conscience which is the judge remember judging us just because our conscience says something is wrong or something is bad doesn't mean to say we have to accept it because sometimes this judge is a tyrant sometimes the conscience is too tight and it creates a life of dread creates a life of unnecessary shame on the other hand this conscience can sometimes be very loose

164
00:22:32,291 --> 00:22:36,195
so that we don't feel appropriate shame, appropriate dread when we do things.

165
00:22:37,377 --> 00:22:40,601
So we haven't got to trust our conscience.

166
00:22:40,621 --> 00:22:54,856
There has to be, as it were, some sort of reflection about it and talking to other people whom you trust so that there's a balance in the mind knowing what is good, what is bad,

167
00:22:55,208 --> 00:23:02,858
at a basic moral level, but remember that at a more refined level, it's what's skillful and unskillful.

168
00:23:03,960 --> 00:23:13,353
And when the Buddha talks about what is skillful and unskillful, he's always talking about that which leads to the liberation and that which leads to suffering.

169
00:23:17,659 --> 00:23:23,847
Those two emotions that we feel, dread and shame, shame is...

170
00:23:24,992 --> 00:23:54,425
that feeling of loss of self-esteem we haven't lived up to our own standards that's why we blush and dread is the fear of consequences the fear of consequences now when we do something harmful and we feel shame and dread in a sense that is not to be seen as a punishment

171
00:23:54,962 --> 00:23:56,424
That's how people would look upon it.

172
00:23:56,444 --> 00:23:58,728
It's not to be seen as a punishment, but as warnings.

173
00:24:00,570 --> 00:24:11,967
When we accept the factors of shame and dread, and they become, as it were, part and parcel of our psychology, they prevent us from doing things.

174
00:24:12,146 --> 00:24:20,239
Because as soon as you think, well, I'll do that, there comes just that little bite of shame, just that little bite of dread, and it stops you.

175
00:24:21,701 --> 00:24:24,884
And it's when shame and dread are behaving like this

176
00:24:25,220 --> 00:24:27,865
that the Buddha calls them guardians of society.

177
00:24:32,116 --> 00:24:42,080
You can see from the way, for instance, a lot of the youth behave, that the line they draw about shame and dread is pretty low.

178
00:24:42,297 --> 00:24:48,105
They can do certain things which they're not ashamed of, nor do they dread any consequence.

179
00:24:48,885 --> 00:24:55,253
So you can see that once these reactions are lowered, you're going to get behaviour which is unsociable.

180
00:24:56,296 --> 00:25:03,144
When there's no shame and dread there, then we're talking about psychopaths, we're talking about sociopaths.

181
00:25:03,164 --> 00:25:05,367
It's an actual psychological disease.

182
00:25:10,748 --> 00:25:29,736
Remorse, on the other side, is suddenly feeling that compunction, that desire to be rid of all the guilt and the shame and to want to be reconciled with the person whom you've hurt or indeed who's hurt you.

183
00:25:29,756 --> 00:25:37,768
So remorse is a natural feeling which comes after we accept that we've done wrong.

184
00:25:39,402 --> 00:25:42,185
And in our meditation, we have to sit with that.

185
00:25:42,586 --> 00:25:45,391
If you try and block it out, you'll just harden your heart.

186
00:25:46,853 --> 00:25:49,837
You must respond to that desire to be reconciled.

187
00:25:51,921 --> 00:25:53,884
To go to the person, if necessary.

188
00:25:54,324 --> 00:25:57,288
But in some way, that remorse has to be answered.

189
00:25:58,329 --> 00:26:01,494
And it's going through that cycle of...

190
00:26:02,166 --> 00:26:23,455
guilt, shame, feeling bad about oneself, fearful of consequences, feeling remorse, and bringing that remorse to an end by reconciliation, that there's not only a process of healing at that particular event, but also undermining that whole conditioning.

191
00:26:26,180 --> 00:26:29,523
So eventually we don't get ourselves into those corners.

192
00:26:29,740 --> 00:26:35,868
Now what helps us is that our conditioning is always fairly much the same.

193
00:26:36,250 --> 00:26:37,832
This is what we mean by karma.

194
00:26:38,953 --> 00:26:40,556
We're always doing the same thing.

195
00:26:40,895 --> 00:26:42,519
We're always making the same mistake.

196
00:26:42,558 --> 00:26:50,871
If you look back on your life or whatever, you'll always see that there's a trait within us which is always popping up, given the occasion it comes up.

197
00:26:52,031 --> 00:26:52,291
See?

198
00:26:52,633 --> 00:27:00,865
And it's catching that right before it comes up and letting it go, not responding to it, that undermines that whole trait.

199
00:27:01,846 --> 00:27:02,886
And why do we do it?

200
00:27:03,127 --> 00:27:07,733
Because we've recognised it leads nowhere but to suffering, to our discomfort.

201
00:27:15,404 --> 00:27:17,989
So now we have to go a little deeper because...

202
00:27:19,825 --> 00:27:29,436
In a sense, that tells us how we cause ourselves to suffer, and it tells us how to get rid of it.

203
00:27:30,218 --> 00:27:37,646
But the next point on the wheel of dependent origination to investigate is that whole point at the beginning of it, which is avijja.

204
00:27:38,667 --> 00:27:41,550
Now, avijja is translated as ignorance.

205
00:27:41,570 --> 00:27:43,012
That's how it's normally translated.

206
00:27:43,413 --> 00:27:47,959
But in English, ignorance has a feeling of stupidity about it.

207
00:27:48,799 --> 00:27:51,042
But that's not really the meaning.

208
00:27:51,243 --> 00:27:57,573
The meaning, I came across this word, nescience, which fits it more beautifully.

209
00:27:58,233 --> 00:28:00,336
And nescience just means don't know.

210
00:28:00,356 --> 00:28:02,700
I just don't know.

211
00:28:02,740 --> 00:28:13,316
Now, in the Buddha's understanding, when consciousness arises, it arises from a base of don't know.

212
00:28:13,355 --> 00:28:16,140
And

213
00:28:16,508 --> 00:28:45,115
it moves into this body and mind body mind and heart and it simply presumes this is what it is therefore you form eventually a concept of yourself I am who I am I'm here I'm my personality my character I'm my body I'm my emotions etc etc see that little mistake is actually the fundamental cause for all the bit that we've just discussed

214
00:28:47,238 --> 00:29:10,561
Now if we go back on that and we recognize that right at the very beginning there's been a mistake, it was a mistake, that if it weren't for that mistake we would never have done any harm, then you begin to understand that at fundament we're innocent.

215
00:29:10,846 --> 00:29:16,732
It's only because of a mistake, not because of something culpable, not because of something blameworthy.

216
00:29:17,093 --> 00:29:18,054
We just made a mistake.

217
00:29:20,297 --> 00:29:28,086
Now, I'll give you an example of that just from one of my experiences when I was in Sri Lanka.

218
00:29:28,105 --> 00:29:32,631
They had these very nasty little flies called Ohopatua.

219
00:29:32,652 --> 00:29:33,451
Have I said that properly?

220
00:29:34,212 --> 00:29:36,516
Ohopatua.

221
00:29:37,946 --> 00:29:46,794
They're just little gnats, they fly in the air, and they have a nasty habit of biting you and leaving you with a very itchy pimple for about three days.

222
00:29:48,736 --> 00:29:52,259
And sometimes they even can creep through a mosquito net.

223
00:29:53,099 --> 00:30:07,751
So here I am with these little pimples and scratching them, and I'm wondering what to do, and I suddenly realize that a spider has built a web in the cootie, in the room, in the hut.

224
00:30:08,221 --> 00:30:14,268
So I say to myself, that's it, I've got to get spiders in and that'll get rid of them.

225
00:30:14,288 --> 00:30:14,367
See?

226
00:30:14,387 --> 00:30:16,770
So I have little signs up saying, this way please.

227
00:30:17,791 --> 00:30:19,314
Yeah?

228
00:30:19,334 --> 00:30:22,277
Well, within a few days, there were hundreds of them.

229
00:30:22,297 --> 00:30:24,159
They were everywhere, all around the room.

230
00:30:24,839 --> 00:30:26,741
And I thought, well, this is really crazy.

231
00:30:26,801 --> 00:30:32,048
And it was getting to a point where I was so bitten and miserable that I decided, you know, I've just got to leave.

232
00:30:32,067 --> 00:30:33,269
I've got to go up country somewhere.

233
00:30:33,670 --> 00:30:35,291
Just get out of these flies.

234
00:30:35,508 --> 00:30:43,765
Happily, just at that time, a friend of mine, a Canadian monk came and I told him, you know, looking really grim that this was it.

235
00:30:43,785 --> 00:30:46,309
And I showed him my pimples and I said, look at this.

236
00:30:47,553 --> 00:30:54,047
And he looked around and he said, these spiders webs, don't you get rid of spiders, the webs out of your room?

237
00:30:54,667 --> 00:30:55,189
I said, no.

238
00:30:55,429 --> 00:30:56,672
He said, well, they breed on those.

239
00:30:57,461 --> 00:31:00,046
See?

240
00:31:00,066 --> 00:31:06,836
So here's a wonderful occasion where innocent ignorance, you see, leads me into suffering.

241
00:31:08,519 --> 00:31:10,582
Now, at fundament, that's all the Buddha's saying.

242
00:31:10,981 --> 00:31:13,145
All he's saying is that we've made a mistake.

243
00:31:15,067 --> 00:31:15,229
See?

244
00:31:15,910 --> 00:31:17,952
We're never meant to do any harm.

245
00:31:18,773 --> 00:31:21,478
And so at fundament, we are innocent.

246
00:31:23,467 --> 00:31:37,037
If we weren't, if it was actually part of our essential nature not to be innocent, then how could we ever become enlightened?

247
00:31:43,057 --> 00:31:49,445
Just one or two, well, maybe one reflection on existential guilt.

248
00:31:50,047 --> 00:31:58,758
This really refers to people who have been brought up in Christianity or a religion which has a god.

249
00:32:01,740 --> 00:32:07,107
Because according to those religions,

250
00:32:08,017 --> 00:32:10,059
we are born evil.

251
00:32:10,621 --> 00:32:21,538
In Buddhism, evil and all that is a secondary thing, which means that Western people can suffer from what you might call an existential guilt.

252
00:32:21,557 --> 00:32:24,542
In other words, they feel themselves to be essentially evil.

253
00:32:26,506 --> 00:32:30,732
In so doing, you can see the necessity of

254
00:32:31,422 --> 00:32:44,237
having someone to intercede, somebody who can save, can take away that essential evil, and thereby find some reconciliation with God.

255
00:32:44,277 --> 00:32:45,999
You see?

256
00:32:46,699 --> 00:32:52,665
Now, if you're a Westerner and you're brought up on that, you see, then that will probably be somewhere in your psyche.

257
00:32:53,507 --> 00:32:56,770
So that also has to be suffered and allowed to pass away.

258
00:32:57,432 --> 00:32:57,711
You see?

259
00:32:58,252 --> 00:32:59,994
And sometimes that goes very deep.

260
00:33:01,056 --> 00:33:01,175
Right?

261
00:33:01,949 --> 00:33:07,258
And when you couple it with the idea of eternal damnation, then that's bad news.

262
00:33:08,058 --> 00:33:16,212
So what we have to do is go underneath that and really accept those sorts of feelings.

263
00:33:16,232 --> 00:33:19,198
And they can be extraordinarily nasty.

264
00:33:19,499 --> 00:33:23,084
like fear, you know, and dread and all that sort of stuff.

265
00:33:23,104 --> 00:33:32,576
But you have to stay there, you have to feel it, you see, you have to investigate it and recognize your reaction to it, which is of course that we don't want to feel that.

266
00:33:32,596 --> 00:33:39,346
And eventually as that evaporates, that essential innocence arises.

267
00:33:39,529 --> 00:33:44,257
Now, there is a movement in Christianity where they don't talk about original sin.

268
00:33:44,497 --> 00:33:45,519
That's what they're referring to.

269
00:33:45,558 --> 00:33:50,506
Most of you will know the myth of Adam and Eve in the Garden of Eden.

270
00:33:51,047 --> 00:33:59,077
But you'll also find that there are, shall we say, movements in Christianity that, instead of talking about that, talk about the original blessing.

271
00:33:59,218 --> 00:34:02,482
In other words, the fact was that Adam and Eve

272
00:34:02,462 --> 00:34:05,049
were born in innocent happiness.

273
00:34:06,232 --> 00:34:10,083
So in that sense they come closer to a Buddhist understanding.

274
00:34:11,266 --> 00:34:18,344
So there is an end to guilt, there is an end to shame, and there is therefore an end to forgiveness.

275
00:34:26,797 --> 00:34:31,483
Just two things that always come up whenever I discuss this.

276
00:34:31,543 --> 00:34:35,347
First of all, why is it that some people get away with it?

277
00:34:36,188 --> 00:34:40,875
I mean, they seem to die.

278
00:34:41,014 --> 00:34:42,416
I mean, take Stalin, for instance.

279
00:34:42,456 --> 00:34:46,501
He died fairly happily in bed, having murdered 40 million people.

280
00:34:47,003 --> 00:34:54,271
And it seems to have got everything he wanted, although he must have been in a dreadful state of mind in a way, because he only worked at night and...

281
00:34:54,251 --> 00:35:05,592
I think on one trip he had five trains going, all giving the impression that he was on one of them, constantly in dread of being assassinated.

282
00:35:06,775 --> 00:35:11,844
But take that to one side and just say, well, some people seem to get away with it, you see.

283
00:35:12,025 --> 00:35:14,369
Well, here, of course...

284
00:35:15,784 --> 00:35:45,791
we have to, in a sense, open towards the acceptance of the idea of rebirth, the idea that perhaps this isn't the only life we've ever lived, and it's not the only life we're going to live, and that there is some sort of justice in the process of the world in which individual consciousnesses, shall we say, do work their way up towards the enlightenment through a process of being born and being reborn.

285
00:35:45,771 --> 00:36:02,514
However, if a person finds that difficult to accept, it's not actually necessary in order to get the benefits of the psychology that we've just been explaining, because the benefits of that are immediate.

286
00:36:03,219 --> 00:36:18,271
through the practice of insight meditation, to seeing that we cause ourselves suffering, and to see that we cause ourselves suffering when we cause others, when we press other people's buttons, is immediate.

287
00:36:18,532 --> 00:36:22,460
We immediately stop behaving in certain ways and we feel happier for it.

288
00:36:22,896 --> 00:36:26,322
But in a cosmic sense, this was one of the insights of the Buddha.

289
00:36:26,903 --> 00:36:42,492
It was part of his enlightenment, when he saw that people were dying and going elsewhere, and that a great deal of the reason for their going where they were going was because of their bodily behavior, which creates these dispositions within us.

290
00:36:45,577 --> 00:36:54,873
And finally, there's a real difficult one, which is very hard for people to accept, who haven't come across this psychology before.

291
00:36:54,893 --> 00:36:58,699
And that's, of course, the suffering of innocence, especially the suffering of a child.

292
00:37:00,541 --> 00:37:02,264
But it is the same.

293
00:37:02,706 --> 00:37:04,268
It is the same psychology.

294
00:37:05,009 --> 00:37:06,572
What is horrific...

295
00:37:07,025 --> 00:37:22,503
to us about a child's situation is of course its absolute vulnerability and its inability through language or conceptual reasoning to find any distance or objectivity to the suffering that it's undergoing.

296
00:37:24,605 --> 00:37:35,056
But still, you know, the child ends up with a trauma and in a sense the rest of its life is working out that psychological trauma within itself.

297
00:37:35,358 --> 00:37:39,744
And it's very rare, I think, for a person not to have a childhood trauma somewhere.

298
00:37:40,927 --> 00:37:46,695
These childhood traumas are not simply caused, are not only caused by people who actually mean to do them harm.

299
00:37:47,155 --> 00:37:51,802
The very process of birth is a trauma, for heaven's sake.

300
00:37:51,822 --> 00:38:01,938
So, the suffering in the child follows the same psychology, and that's why eventually, as adults, we can empty ourselves of this suffering.

301
00:38:04,905 --> 00:38:17,713
Now, for the person who harms a child, well, now that's something else, you see, because they have to now bear the awful responsibility for that child's suffering.

302
00:38:18,496 --> 00:38:23,606
They might not be the direct cause of that suffering, but they were the catalyst that caused it.

303
00:38:24,463 --> 00:38:42,577
And just to give you two wonderful examples that bring that home to us, the Moors murderer, Brady, was asked if he ever thought about the child victims that he tortured and murdered up here just in Lancashire.

304
00:38:43,519 --> 00:38:46,405
And he said, if I did that, it would drive me mad.

305
00:38:47,987 --> 00:38:53,655
Now, some of you may have come across a book called The Man Who Mistook His Wife for a Hat.

306
00:38:54,476 --> 00:38:55,378
You ever come across that one?

307
00:38:57,101 --> 00:38:57,782
It's a really good book.

308
00:38:57,842 --> 00:39:01,106
It's written by a psychologist called Oliver Sacks.

309
00:39:01,126 --> 00:39:04,471
And he's interested in brain damage and the way people are.

310
00:39:04,510 --> 00:39:08,956
The particular title refers to a man who couldn't distinguish objects.

311
00:39:09,478 --> 00:39:15,085
And as he was leaving the office after a talk, he simply grabbed his wife's head, thinking it was his hat.

312
00:39:15,827 --> 00:39:15,987
LAUGHTER

313
00:39:15,967 --> 00:39:45,179
his wife I don't think is all that pleased in that same book there's a very interesting tale which definitely says something to Buddhists there's a man who murders his daughter in such a vicious way that the facts of the case are not brought out in public in the court they're just too horrific this man could not remember a thing

314
00:39:45,346 --> 00:39:52,378
So eventually they had to convict him as insane and they sent him to a secure prison for the mentally insane.

315
00:39:52,559 --> 00:39:53,300
This is in America.

316
00:39:54,181 --> 00:39:55,804
So they couldn't convict him as a straight criminal.

317
00:39:56,867 --> 00:40:08,467
While he was there he acted seemingly quite normal and within a few years the staff had such confidence in him that they let him go out on bicycle rides.

318
00:40:10,202 --> 00:40:17,132
On one of these bicycle rides, a car hit him and he fell over and banged his head on the road.

319
00:40:18,594 --> 00:40:25,202
This had the effect of awakening, when he woke up from the concussion, of awakening in him what he'd actually done.

320
00:40:26,983 --> 00:40:37,036
And so the story goes, it took six months for the staff to restrain and stop him from committing suicide.

321
00:40:39,599 --> 00:40:49,831
So eventually the harm that we do catches up on us and to harm innocence would leave us with an enormous sense of guilt and remorse.

322
00:40:55,960 --> 00:41:03,769
So now we come to well I'll just give you a final reflection on that concerning harm.

323
00:41:04,351 --> 00:41:08,255
There's a very famous simile of the saw which the Buddha gives.

324
00:41:08,422 --> 00:41:22,737
And he says, oh monks, even if bandits were to sever you savagely, limb by limb with a two-handed saw, he who gave rise to hatred towards them would not be carrying out my teaching.

325
00:41:23,838 --> 00:41:28,864
That's heavy, isn't it?

326
00:41:28,884 --> 00:41:32,067
So now what I'd like to do is...

327
00:41:33,092 --> 00:41:37,119
I ask you to do another contemplation exercise.

328
00:41:37,960 --> 00:41:43,128
And the first one is, how do we free ourselves from a victim's suffering?

329
00:41:43,148 --> 00:41:47,315
So from the suffering that we feel when we've been victimized or when we've been a victim.

330
00:41:47,916 --> 00:41:53,103
And the second one is, how do we liberate ourselves from the suffering of being a victimizer?

331
00:41:54,306 --> 00:41:58,391
So I just want to go through these steps and you can sort of close your eyes and just go through them.

332
00:41:59,552 --> 00:42:03,219
And then you'll get an idea of how it might work for you.

333
00:42:04,762 --> 00:42:14,739
So the first one is how to let go of the suffering we feel when we've been hurt.

334
00:42:14,759 --> 00:42:18,967
So the first thing to recognize is that to forgive is not to forget.

335
00:42:19,007 --> 00:42:20,009
You have to be very careful.

336
00:42:20,449 --> 00:42:23,755
If you try and forget the hurt that's been given to you,

337
00:42:24,157 --> 00:42:30,898
then all you're doing is suppressing it and it's just working underground and it works as grudges and it just sabotages our lives.

338
00:42:32,523 --> 00:42:35,213
When we forgive somebody, we're not excusing them either.

339
00:42:36,086 --> 00:42:37,268
I've got a headache or something.

340
00:42:38,969 --> 00:42:45,635
And sometimes we feel that if we forgive somebody, somehow in a secret way we're sort of condoning what they're doing.

341
00:42:45,675 --> 00:42:47,557
So that's not forgiveness either.

342
00:42:48,219 --> 00:43:01,351
Forgiveness is just a change of attitude, a letting go of that hurt, letting go of revenge, and establishing within us that sense of compassion and forgiveness towards the person.

343
00:43:03,880 --> 00:43:09,425
So the first thing, if you now take somebody who's hurt you, it can be somebody real, but not the big one.

344
00:43:14,550 --> 00:43:21,835
The first thing you have to, I think, recognize is that there's no need for us to punish them.

345
00:43:21,856 --> 00:43:25,179
They themselves will suffer the consequences of their own actions.

346
00:43:27,942 --> 00:43:28,983
That's the karmic law.

347
00:43:30,284 --> 00:43:33,347
So there's no need for us to seek revenge.

348
00:43:35,672 --> 00:43:41,541
And a Chinese proverb warns us, those who seek revenge should dig two graves.

349
00:43:44,905 --> 00:43:50,632
The second thing is to remind ourselves that that person originally has made a mistake.

350
00:43:50,713 --> 00:43:55,579
It's by way of delusion that they've come to behave in this unskillful way.

351
00:43:55,960 --> 00:44:02,710
That fundamentally they are actually innocent and they didn't mean to do any harm.

352
00:44:05,001 --> 00:44:21,880
sometimes it's good to have a dialogue with the person in your mind having done that having as it were corrected our relationship to that person we can then turn inward

353
00:44:22,061 --> 00:44:25,306
And just get in contact with the hurt we feel.

354
00:44:25,505 --> 00:44:27,168
You can run through the occasion.

355
00:44:27,188 --> 00:44:29,851
You can bring up the occasion when you were hurt.

356
00:44:30,472 --> 00:44:34,215
Now here you've got to be very careful not to be taken away by fantasy.

357
00:44:34,335 --> 00:44:40,103
So you've got to keep that attention as much as you can right at the physical base.

358
00:44:40,802 --> 00:44:42,905
The feelings around hurt.

359
00:44:48,152 --> 00:44:49,753
The anger that may still come up.

360
00:44:50,353 --> 00:44:51,815
The desire for revenge.

361
00:44:52,065 --> 00:44:58,253
Try and stay as close as you can to the body, to sensation, to feeling.

362
00:45:10,327 --> 00:45:20,318
Now as those feelings begin to decrease, the next step would be to contemplate the other person's better nature.

363
00:45:21,952 --> 00:45:47,284
when all the hurt and the desire for revenge begins to decrease you can then begin to reform your relationship to that person try and see their better nature give them the benefit of the doubt send them good wishes from the heart and if that's too difficult well at least an attitude of no harm that's the base isn't it no harm

364
00:45:59,599 --> 00:46:04,610
So that, as it were, sets our right relationship with the person, right attitude.

365
00:46:05,391 --> 00:46:18,856
Now, in the future, we can resolve not to approach that person concerning this occasion unless we're absolutely equanimous, which means we have to wait for the right time.

366
00:46:29,079 --> 00:46:36,192
And then when we decide that we are going to approach them, to almost talk as if you're a mediator.

367
00:46:37,673 --> 00:46:43,724
You'll be very careful not to put blame, not to lay it on them, but just to be clear about the feelings we felt.

368
00:46:44,485 --> 00:46:47,389
We have to take responsibility for our part in the incident.

369
00:46:53,679 --> 00:46:54,902
Takes two to tango.

370
00:47:01,514 --> 00:47:04,458
And the next thing is not to expect an apology.

371
00:47:04,860 --> 00:47:06,402
That's a presumption on our part.

372
00:47:06,422 --> 00:47:08,686
If they do so, well, of course, it's very healing.

373
00:47:09,748 --> 00:47:14,054
But it's not important to us that they should express an apology.

374
00:47:20,065 --> 00:47:22,829
See, the healing comes by this inner process.

375
00:47:30,775 --> 00:47:35,161
Now sometimes of course we can't do anything because the person's moved on or they may have died.

376
00:47:36,121 --> 00:47:39,266
So we have to work with this process of reconciliation inward.

377
00:47:41,128 --> 00:47:45,313
Until all the emotional pain around the memory is just slowly drained away.

378
00:47:45,353 --> 00:47:52,141
Don't solidify around it, don't get hard around it, just see it as a process.

379
00:47:54,079 --> 00:47:58,425
You can often just sit with an emotion and just say gently, not me, not mine.

380
00:47:58,824 --> 00:48:00,706
It's there, I'm looking at it.

381
00:48:01,728 --> 00:48:04,331
I'm experiencing it, so I can't be it.

382
00:48:10,757 --> 00:48:20,407
So that's one way that you might try in the future to deal with suffering which comes because somebody has victimized you.

383
00:48:22,581 --> 00:48:47,019
If we now go to the other side and consider some of the suffering that we've been a catalyst to in other people, where we've been the victimizer, then it might be a good start to just reflect on the fact that we are fundamentally deluded, that we've acted primordially out of a mistake,

384
00:48:47,336 --> 00:48:55,126
and that we are fundamentally innocent and therefore utter forgiveness of ourselves by ourselves is possible.

385
00:49:07,621 --> 00:49:11,206
Then we have to convince ourselves that of course we do have a responsibility.

386
00:49:12,188 --> 00:49:16,213
We did play a role in causing that person harm, we were a catalyst.

387
00:49:18,150 --> 00:49:26,043
A catalyst in chemistry is something which causes a change, causes a change between two chemicals, but itself doesn't change.

388
00:49:27,385 --> 00:49:39,061
So the word I might have said to somebody doesn't change, or it just hits the same space, but it creates within the other a whole sequence of psychological events that causes them suffering.

389
00:49:39,443 --> 00:49:41,085
We have to take responsibility for that.

390
00:49:42,847 --> 00:49:45,311
Sometimes we know how to press somebody's buttons too.

391
00:49:45,351 --> 00:49:46,773
We enjoy doing it.

392
00:49:54,144 --> 00:49:57,471
But when we do this we have to be careful not to take on false guilt.

393
00:49:58,331 --> 00:50:07,867
We're taking on false guilt if we take on their personal suffering.

394
00:50:07,887 --> 00:50:11,994
So now we make resolutions not to do that again.

395
00:50:12,034 --> 00:50:17,945
So I was very careful about resolutions because you know the old phrase that the path to hell is paved with good resolutions.

396
00:50:18,346 --> 00:50:19,527
So it has to be realistic.

397
00:50:21,043 --> 00:50:23,987
These behavior patterns are deeply ingrained.

398
00:50:24,648 --> 00:50:27,791
They've come to us over a long time.

399
00:50:27,851 --> 00:50:33,398
So we shouldn't be surprised if we keep making the mistake over and over again.

400
00:50:35,179 --> 00:50:40,686
So we have to accept that this process is going to be repeated and repeated and repeated.

401
00:50:41,206 --> 00:50:48,974
And what we're hoping is that given a length of time, the behavior lessens, eventually dies away.

402
00:50:51,487 --> 00:50:55,094
But we still have to make these resolutions, these determinations.

403
00:50:55,755 --> 00:51:04,592
And that determination has to be one of being really awake, really mindful.

404
00:51:05,173 --> 00:51:13,090
The alarm bell should go off whenever we enter a situation where we know we normally do something stupid, something silly, something unskillful.

405
00:51:19,364 --> 00:51:25,230
Then there's the usual business of sitting with the remorse, the shame, the guilt which is in our hearts.

406
00:51:25,710 --> 00:51:29,054
So that's part of the process of vipassana insight meditation.

407
00:51:29,135 --> 00:51:29,815
We can do that.

408
00:51:30,715 --> 00:51:32,297
And we can watch them as a process.

409
00:51:35,461 --> 00:51:43,570
We can see that if we push guilt away, push shame away, or push remorse away, that causes us more suffering.

410
00:51:44,490 --> 00:51:47,835
So there we're catching this process of how we cause ourselves to suffer.

411
00:51:49,806 --> 00:51:57,197
We can so distance ourselves from those emotions within us that they become very objective.

412
00:51:57,938 --> 00:51:59,480
There's shame.

413
00:51:59,500 --> 00:52:00,701
There's the feelings of shame.

414
00:52:00,742 --> 00:52:02,063
There's the feelings of guilt.

415
00:52:03,684 --> 00:52:05,146
And just watch them as a process.

416
00:52:05,527 --> 00:52:08,711
Don't get involved by way of identity or possessing them.

417
00:52:09,193 --> 00:52:10,393
They're not me, not mine.

418
00:52:10,434 --> 00:52:14,699
These are the things that insight meditation teaches us.

419
00:52:22,476 --> 00:52:30,186
Two of our most powerful reasons for hurting people is jealousy and hatred.

420
00:52:30,907 --> 00:52:31,969
All forms of hatred.

421
00:52:32,670 --> 00:52:35,414
So jealousy isn't just a simple covetousness.

422
00:52:35,474 --> 00:52:39,039
It's not just wanting what the other person wants, what the other person has.

423
00:52:39,059 --> 00:52:42,903
It's wanting what the other person has and hating them for having it.

424
00:52:45,306 --> 00:52:51,876
So the antidote to that is having sat with that for a while to begin to rejoice in the other person's good fortune.

425
00:52:53,476 --> 00:52:56,059
This is what we mean by sympathetic joy.

426
00:52:56,980 --> 00:52:58,201
And that's a contemplation.

427
00:52:59,802 --> 00:53:03,588
When somebody wins the lottery, you rejoice for them.

428
00:53:04,708 --> 00:53:07,932
You're happy that a bit of the pound you spent went to their fortune.

429
00:53:10,956 --> 00:53:15,041
When your friend who went with you for the same job gets the job, you rejoice for them.

430
00:53:19,726 --> 00:53:21,507
This sort of thing undermines jealousy.

431
00:53:22,788 --> 00:53:26,733
Hatred is undermined by seeing the other person in a different light.

432
00:53:28,175 --> 00:53:33,804
As we said before, to actually bring to mind their good qualities, so there's a balance of attitude towards them.

433
00:53:38,311 --> 00:53:46,585
And then finally, if it's possible, to meet with the person and express our remorse, express our sorrow.

434
00:53:49,652 --> 00:54:18,461
in the Visuddhimagga it also suggests that we offer them a gift when it's appropriate now supposing at work you'd had a bit of an upset with somebody and you'd gone through this exercise when you go to work and you're walking through that door say of a corridor and they see you at the end of it our ability to

435
00:54:18,829 --> 00:54:22,315
tell where people are at is very refined.

436
00:54:22,715 --> 00:54:29,224
We know from a person's body language, we know from what's on their face, even at quite a distance, whether they're friend or foe.

437
00:54:31,547 --> 00:54:41,782
And this person may be feeling themselves still hardened by what they did, or they may feel remorse themselves, or they may feel a desire to be reconciled rather.

438
00:54:42,978 --> 00:54:49,565
Just by having that attitude, it'll show on our face, it'll show on the way that we walk.

439
00:54:52,469 --> 00:54:56,353
So that they know there's a desire in us to be reconciled.

440
00:55:00,217 --> 00:55:12,731
So these things are really very important preparatory exercises, so that when we actually meet up with people whom we've hurt, they're open to our apology.

441
00:55:15,478 --> 00:55:28,141
Now the fact is that, generally speaking, unless they've been fortunate enough to come to the Buddha's teaching about pain, they will definitely blame you for the suffering they're suffering.

442
00:55:28,161 --> 00:55:28,742
That's what they do.

443
00:55:29,163 --> 00:55:30,264
That's what people do.

444
00:55:31,492 --> 00:55:44,847
Now, that doesn't mean to say you have to take on their suffering, but there's no point in going into a great dissertation about how they're causing themselves suffering and that your insult didn't actually cause them to suffer.

445
00:55:45,387 --> 00:55:46,550
That won't do at all.

446
00:55:46,630 --> 00:55:50,393
All they think you're doing is trying to escape your responsibility.

447
00:55:52,396 --> 00:55:53,356
So we apologize.

448
00:55:53,396 --> 00:55:54,157
That's not a problem.

449
00:55:54,177 --> 00:55:58,782
We apologize, but in our hearts we apologize for our part in the process.

450
00:55:59,759 --> 00:56:00,260
That's enough.

451
00:56:00,579 --> 00:56:07,510
You don't have to explain anything.

452
00:56:07,530 --> 00:56:12,958
What happens now if the person refuses to forgive, harbours vengefulness, resentment?

453
00:56:15,342 --> 00:56:16,182
What can we do about that?

454
00:56:18,726 --> 00:56:20,048
We don't have an option, really, do we?

455
00:56:20,188 --> 00:56:24,635
We have to accept that this person now sees themselves as an enemy.

456
00:56:26,606 --> 00:56:34,677
So that will also create a reaction within us, maybe fear, maybe also a desire to set up battle formations.

457
00:56:38,262 --> 00:56:42,128
But because of this psychology they can't actually do us any harm.

458
00:56:43,329 --> 00:56:52,782
Outside they might, they might slander us, they might undermine us in all sorts of ways, but inwardly they're not doing us, they're not causing any suffering.

459
00:56:55,699 --> 00:57:00,286
So often when you get a person like that, it's often best just to stay out of their way.

460
00:57:01,349 --> 00:57:04,934
Because even the sight of you raises heckles.

461
00:57:11,425 --> 00:57:14,130
And hopefully there comes a time when you can be reconciled.

462
00:57:17,130 --> 00:57:30,092
It also takes a bit of philosophy to recognize, well, when you do something into the world, you never know what the consequences are going to be, because it enters into a situation over which we don't have control.

463
00:57:33,898 --> 00:57:43,914
You may one day say something flippant to somebody, and, I mean, they take it, they laugh it off, and nothing ever comes of it, because they're a forgiving type.

464
00:57:44,164 --> 00:58:13,311
you may say the very same thing with the same slight and with the same sort of slight sarcastic joke and somebody takes it as a personal hatred and off they go on a vendetta from your point of view it's the same input into the world but you hadn't a clue it was going to come back to you so when something comes back to you which seems to be completely inappropriate to what you did then that's a lesson to understand

465
00:58:21,306 --> 00:58:28,907
Finally, I'd like to leave you with a little exercise, which at the moment I've called four steps to determination.

466
00:58:30,572 --> 00:58:33,460
So when you see in yourself a trait which you don't like,

467
00:58:35,228 --> 00:58:43,619
then you have to make a determination, you have to go through something of this nature to undermine that particular trait.

468
00:58:44,360 --> 00:58:49,987
So supposing you do have a certain sarcastic twist to the way you say things.

469
00:58:50,387 --> 00:58:57,597
So the first thing is that you have to convince yourself that you can undo that particular conditioning.

470
00:58:58,177 --> 00:58:59,500
So you have to say to yourself, I can.

471
00:58:59,519 --> 00:59:04,847
You have to keep saying that until you convince yourself that you're able to do it, just by letting it go.

472
00:59:05,384 --> 00:59:08,010
just by not indulging it, the habit will die out.

473
00:59:09,635 --> 00:59:18,717
Then you have to reinforce that can-do with a sense of ought, a sense of responsibility, taking one's responsibility for one's own self.

474
00:59:19,373 --> 00:59:33,048
Now, these words like ought, must, have to, tend to be looked down upon, especially in psychotherapeutic circles, because they cause further blame, they cause a further guilt when you don't fulfill what you said you would do.

475
00:59:33,869 --> 00:59:36,492
But that's only when it's imposed upon us.

476
00:59:37,793 --> 00:59:44,402
If we ourselves take responsibility, then they become ours, so it's easy to do it.

477
00:59:44,956 --> 00:59:49,581
So I ought to do it for my own benefit and others is an act of compassion on my part.

478
00:59:49,722 --> 00:59:52,204
It's a compassion towards myself and a compassion to others.

479
00:59:53,266 --> 00:59:56,969
I'm motivated to do what is good for myself and other people.

480
00:59:58,172 --> 01:00:01,215
So that ought is not something which is going to cause any trouble.

481
01:00:03,717 --> 01:00:06,762
Then you've got to convince yourself that you want to do it.

482
01:00:06,842 --> 01:00:09,009
And you may find that a bit of a sticking point.

483
01:00:09,469 --> 01:00:10,713
So you've got to cajole yourself.

484
01:00:10,994 --> 01:00:11,896
You do want to do it.

485
01:00:11,936 --> 01:00:16,009
You have to convince yourself to give up a habit which you don't want.

486
01:00:16,951 --> 01:00:23,757
And then finally when you feel there is that desire to give it up, a real committed desire, then you have to empower it.

487
01:00:23,797 --> 01:00:24,538
You have to say, I will.

488
01:00:25,199 --> 01:00:25,619
I will.

489
01:00:27,059 --> 01:00:32,324
And then you make the decision that whenever that particular trait comes up, I will resist it.

490
01:00:33,025 --> 01:00:33,967
I will resist it.

491
01:00:34,347 --> 01:00:46,197
So these four stages of convincing ourselves that we can do it, that it's our responsibility for the benefit of ourselves and others, that we actually do want to do it, and that we will do it,

492
01:00:46,567 --> 01:00:52,458
you'll find I think fairly powerful in helping you to get rid of unwanted

493
01:00:52,641 --> 01:01:17,315
traits in our personalities the opposite is also true it works for positive so if you want to become more generous you have to convince yourself that you can be that you ought to be for your own benefit and others that you want to be you can be stuck there see and then you will so any given occasion you'll express your generosity see

494
01:01:34,710 --> 01:01:42,713
I think that brings us to the end of my little effort to explain how it is that we can come to the end of forgiveness.

495
01:01:44,262 --> 01:01:49,213
So we've done two major things to understand.

496
01:01:49,253 --> 01:02:08,481
First of all, the psychological process as to how suffering arises in us because of our reactions to things that hurt us and because of behaving from an attitude which is unskillful, cruelty, hatred and all that.

